## 1. Introduction

For this assessment, I created a simple website analytics dashboard using Grafana Cloud. The goal was to take a CSV file containing one week of website data and turn it into a dashboard that is easier to understand than looking at raw data in a spreadsheet.

The dataset was created my AI and it contains three columns: Date, Page Views, and Signups. I used this data to create two visualizations as required.

## 2. The Problem

The website data was originally stored in a CSV file. While this is useful for storing data, it is not always easy to quickly understand trends by looking at rows of numbers.

For example, a business owner may want to know if website traffic is increasing or how many users signed up during the week. 
They would have to manually look through the data or calculate the total.


## 3. Solution

I used Grafana Cloud to create a dashboard using the website analytics data. I uploaded the csv file and selected which columns for each panel. 
Before the panels work, all columns must have specified data types. 

The dashboard contains exactly two panels:

### Page Views Over Time

The first panel is a line chart showing Page Views across the seven days. 
I chose a line chart because it makes it easier to see if the values increase or decrease.

### Total Signups

The second panel is a Stat panel showing the total number of Signups. 
The total number of signups in the dataset is 442. Using a Stat panel I used the total settings so we didnt have to calculate manually. 

## 4. Implementation

The main steps I followed were:

1. Created a CSV file containing one week of website analytics data.
2. Set up a Grafana Cloud environment.
3. Connected the website analytics data to Grafana Cloud.
4. Configured the data so the Date, Page Views, and Signups fields were read correctly.
5. Created a new Grafana dashboard.
6. Added a line chart for Page Views over time.
7. Added a Stat panel for Total Signups.
8. Checked the dashboard values against the original CSV data.
9. Exported the completed dashboard as a JSON file.

One of the main things I had to figure out was how to get the CSV data working correctly with Grafana Cloud. 
I also had to make sure the different fields were interpreted correctly so that the dates could be used for the line chart 
and the numerical values could be used in the visualizations. 

## 5. Results

The final dashboard successfully displays the website analytics data in a more visual format.

The Page Views line chart makes it easier to see how website traffic changes throughout the week, while the Stat panel clearly shows the total number of Signups.

The dashboard contains the two required panels. I also exported the dashboard configuration as a JSON file, which is included with the project files.

## 6. Why Use a Dashboard?

A CSV or Excel file is useful for storing raw data, but a dashboard makes the information easier to understand quickly.

Instead of manually comparing Page Views for each day, a user can look at the line chart and immediately see the overall trend. The Stat panel also provides the total number of Signups without requiring any manual calculations.

For a business owner, this makes it easier to quickly understand the website's performance and identify useful information without having to analyze the raw data themselves.

## 7. Conclusion

This project helped me understand the basic process of taking raw data and turning it into a visual dashboard using Grafana Cloud.

I learned that creating a dashboard is not just about choosing graphs. The data also needs to be connected and configured correctly before it can be visualized. I also learned that different visualizations are useful for different types of data.
